2026-04-16 12:16:31 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control Module 7', 'Control Module 8', 'Load Module', 'cable connections between output of Control Module 6 and input of Control Module 7', 'cable connections between output of Control Module 7 and input of Control Module 8', 'cable connections between output of Control Module 8 and input of Load Module'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements prove that 12 V is present up to the input of Control Module 6 but not beyond its output, yet continuity tests show the internal 12 V path of Control Module 6 (input + to output + with switch ON) is intact and correctly wired, and its missing indicator LED/resistor branch should not interrupt the series feed. Therefore the earlier observation of 0 V on the output side must originate from something downstream of Module 6 loading or shorting the line, not from an open or mis‑wired Module 6 itself (which has already been replaced/verified good).\n\nIf any of the downstream modules or the intermodule cables after Module 6 were shorting the +12 V to 0 V, then with the supply referenced at the PSU negative all points beyond the short would sit essentially at 0 V on both conductors, exactly as observed. This fault would also prevent any downstream indicator LEDs and the final lamp from lighting, while leaving the upstream modules (1–5) and the PSU LED operating normally—matching the reported symptoms.\n\nThus the most plausible root cause is a short or incorrect wiring in the downstream chain: one of Control Module 7, Control Module 8, the Load Module, or the cable pairs connecting 6→7, 7→8, or 8→Load is effectively shorting the line (or otherwise mis‑connected) so that the 12 V supply collapses right after Control Module 6. Repair should focus on inspecting and correcting/replacing these modules and their cable connections.'
